fields.descriptive_line: Album of Offering Envelopes for Children; Japanese about 1994
fields.physical_description:
1. album containing Japanese offering envelopes for children: the album is of landscape proportions, and is covered with paper patterned in red, gold, blue, navy, green, brown, gilt and white, of the type used for the Girls' Festival Emperor & Empress dolls to sit on.  The album contains pages fitted with clear cellophane pockets containing offering envelopes.

3. (sample) offering envelope, folded oblong of ivory paper with a gold and silver spatter design, the front decorated with origami figures of the Emperor & Empress dolls and a coloured paper border. 12 x 6.8 cm.  Same as (26)
4. (sample) offering envelope, part-sealed oblong of red & white paper with a black panel, decorated at the front with a noshi (Shinto blessing symbol) of a knot of three red strings & a gold paper fan.  10 x 6.2 cm.  Same as (43).

fields.object: Album of offering envelopes for children
fields.history_note: Assembled by the donor.  In Japan it was once customary to give gifts of money on many occasions: the money must be new (except on sorrowful occasions, when it must be used money) & enclosed in special 'offering envelopes'.  The amounts were often small, the pleasure being in the attractive envelopes, and children would often make collections of them.
